Just as a new appetite for one-stop, self-service shopping led to supermarkets after the First World War, the pandemic could inaugurate a seismic shift in grocery shoppers’ habits.
Read: Grocery stores are the coronavirus tipping pointLockdown is temporary, not a way of life.
Bryan Leach, the CEO of the digital-shopping-promotions company Ibotta, predicts that online grocery shopping will rise from 3 percent “into the double-digits” as a result of the pandemic.
That’s a big change, but it would still see the majority of food shopping happen where it always has, in the stores.
If online grocery can supply the basics, that could be a boon for Main Street–style local shopping.